b'' b'the multi-lingual archives at the computing research labs, new mexico' b'state university will be moving to a new ftp address soon. the' b'archives are being put under control of the consortium for lexical' b'research.' b'' b'the new ftp address will be: clr.nmsu.edu (the current ip address' b'is but may change, so use clr.nmsu.edu whenever' b'possible).' b'' b'please note that there is a difference between ftp sites crl.nmsu.edu and' b'clr.nmsu.edu. the crl.nmsu.edu site will be our ftp site for items' b'not related to the consortium for lexical research.' b'' b'the arabic, chinese, french, italian, indian, japanese, korean,' b'tibetan, and vietnamese archives will all be moved.' b'' b'we will announce the new locations of the relevant directories once' b'the archives have been moved.' b'' b'please be patient if you discover directories missing when you ftp to' b'either crl.nmsu.edu or clr.nmsu.edu. it will take a few days to move' b'everything.' b'' b'if you are not familiar with our multi-lingual archives, we have been' b'slowly collecting various software, fonts, and text for different' b'languages over the past years. most of the software is currently' b'unix oriented. we would also like to encourage people to continue to' b'contribute items to the archives to help improve the quality and' b'quantity of multi-lingual tools.' b'' b'if you have an item to contribute, please put it in:' b'' b'clr.nmsu.edu:incoming/' b'' b'contribution.' b'' b'if you have any questions or comments, please send them to:' b'' b'-----------------------------------------------------------------------------' b'mark leisher' b'computing research lab "elegance is not optional!"' b"new mexico state university attributed to richard o'keefe" b'box 3crl, las cruces, nm 